		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Google Researches Alternative Authentication Methods
				</h2>
				

						
							
							
							
						
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1769482">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<a href="http://www.wired.com/wiredenterprise/2013/01/google-password/all/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.wired.com/wiredenterprise...-password/all/</a><br />
Trying to get all websites everywhere to support a hardware device is not going to happen.  People are also going to lose or not carry additional items just for the purpose of authenticating.  It has to be more convenient than simple passwords as the typical users does not care about security at all even if that is a long term worse outcome for them.  They are short sighted so the complete apathy of most users needs to be the most important aspect the solution is designed to account for.  <br />
<br />
Instead Google should push its own Google authentication design that is exceptional and use that for everything possible and have the option of only the device being the authentication mechanism, which while the security sensitive people would utilize the two-factor security still, removing passwords entirely for the apathetic would be a huge boon for everyone on the net.  It could achieve what OpenID should have, removing every website that requires an account from being an attack vector, amplifying the impact of break ins into a corporation as password reuse is common.  Google should utilize both a smart phone option or having the hardware device like Blizzard does for battle.net to great success.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
