				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Google Researches Alternative Authentication Methods
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1769571">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Solesk</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1769484#post1769484" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">You don't necessarily need websites to support it.  There are a couple of options.<br />
<br />
1) Google allows websites to partner with them and use google login to identify users.  Websites wouldn't need to do much at all.<br />
<br />
2) Lastpass offers the option of connecting a Yubico key to your account.  So you could use a service like them to create individual passwords for every website, and lock them down with a key.  While not completely as secure, it's a very positive step.<br />
<br />
Google also has an authenticator app for android already.  I use it and it's wonderful.  You can even use the app to secure your lastpass login, which I also do.  Oddly though they don't really seem to advertise it, I only found it by searching specifically for it after my gmail was hacked a few years ago.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Yeah, I was referring to their authenticator app, which is why their choice to go to a hardware option is weird to me since the software option has a lot of benefits.  Buy lastpass, tie google hardware to it, rebrand last pass possibly, profit.  I am 100% stoked on lastpass.  I even got my technical confused relatives to use it as it is easier than tryign to remember any of them.  They are really happy too.  I do pay for the mobile thing but it is only like 2 bucks a year so who even cares about 2 dollars a year.  I likely sweat more water out a day than that costs.<br />
<br />
The reason lastpass would be a good purchase is that it has a big user base already and brand recognition so getting those users to fold into the google auth camp would be trivial.  Only reason I won't be using the Google hardware deal, even though it is cool, is that the iPhone and iPad don't have the connectors it uses and running a convertor cable and that would be excessive to tote around all the time.  If a lightning connector version came out though I would definitely pick one up even if it was like 50 bucks.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
