				<div class="imlinks">
					    
				</div>
			
		</div>
		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Google Researches Alternative Authentication Methods
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1769573">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Sehra</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1769488#post1769488" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I don't know if it's fair to call people &quot;apathetic&quot; over this. I remember reading a paper -- pretty recently? -- about the economic argument for usable security. They made a compelling case that people are making the _rational choice_ from an economic perspective when they disregard draconian security measures.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I haven't read the paper, but I agree that it seems like the rational choice, my counter argument is that while it is the rational choice in the short term that the insecure passwords will be trivial to break into and also if the people who have those passwords stored are broken into, well we've seen many cases of how even big corps due very insecure, lazy security measures, and as a result all users are exposed to that.  With the hardware only option or 2 factor option even if the break in occurs, it won't mean anything as they still won't have the necessary pin code.  So, that is why they are better in terms of protection, but the reason they are a long term better rational decision is that the potential impact of the account break in happening (in either scenario) will have such a negative impact on the person's life depending on the site it pertains to that it grossly overtakes how much time savings had been saved up to that time.<br />
<br />
That is why I try to do as much security measures as is reasonable even though it seems like overkill.  The downside of having my laptop stolen and sensitive information gathered on it is very harmful so I always use encryption, at least with the home folder and prefer full disk encryption.  I use lastpass for the aforementioned reasons and it is easy as hell and faster.  I use secure backups because why not? The insecure methods has the same downsides as the laptop scenario except it is even worse.  In that case the number of people who have it is vastly greater and the information is easier to share.  I read one case where a lawyer had that happen on his dropbox account and it was a big deal for him.  Since then he no longer uses dropbox (for good reasons).  I liked that service but they are so horribly incompetent and insecure that it makes no sense unless you have a set up to use dm-crypt, but that is only easy to use on Linux really.  Support on windows and mac is not so great and a big pain or I would use that and dropbox as dropbox's price per gigabyte of storage is the cheapest when I checked last.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
		<div class="postfoot">
			<!-- <div class="postfoot_container"> -->
