		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Google Researches Alternative Authentication Methods
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1769626">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>FilanFyretracker</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1769624#post1769624" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">The big issue with security is the password itself. The very nature of just a password is weak as computing power grows and grows the common criminal will gain access to multiple arrays of Nvidia Tesla units that can do huge amounts of computing. Causing a need for longer passwords. The problem is we eventually hit a point beyond which a person can remember a truly secure password.<br />
<br />
2 factor is the future I think, it will have to be because the lone password is no longer sustainable.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I had started to get to the point that I had a draft email with password hints to myself for the various sites. Part of the problem is some sites, when you forget your password and trigger a reset, won't allow you to use a password you've used before. So I slowly but inevitably get 'password drift/fragmentation' over time - which only gets worse as the number of passwords I have in active use grows.<br />
<br />
I actually just installed lastpass as a direct result of MI's last two posts and it has essentially removed the problem at a stroke. I now have 20 char random passwords with upper/lower/numeric/symbols - a unique one for every website - and it could as easily be 128 char as 20 char with no extra effort on my behalf, so it'll never become insecure.<br />
<br />
Two-factor is definitely stronger - but you can set up lastpass to need physical authentication so that's a pretty good option also.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
